Attaching a snapshot

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8822956/75936035-e4048300-5e35-11ea-92a6-525145167088.png)

Python has 2 outputs corresponding to "1609".  But C# has just 1 output entry from 1609

@yufenglee

@abgoswam , as we synced, this model is weird with duplicated outputs 1609, but onnx spec doesn't specify it is invalid. 
The reason C# has one less output is because C# uses a dictionary for the output meta: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/6a0ee7eff6ce42935c73e52f88fb6d48eb1ea53c/csharp/src/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/InferenceSession.cs#L246

> @abgoswam , as we synced, this model is weird with duplicated outputs 1609, but onnx spec doesn't specify it is invalid.
> The reason C# has one less output is because C# uses a dictionary for the output meta:
> 
> https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/6a0ee7eff6ce42935c73e52f88fb6d48eb1ea53c/csharp/src/Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime/InferenceSession.cs#L246

from https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/IR.md
"The graph MUST adhere to single static assignment (SSA) for all node outputs; this means that all node output names MUST be unique within a graph."
see example of such an issue in the early days of onnx: https://github.com/onnx/models/issues/2

Thanks @jywu-msft ! This issue is different from the onnx/models#2. Here the output name of node Add is unique:1609, but it is added twice to the output of the graph. We discussed this issue, and think it is not reasonable to have duplicate output for graph. ONNX will add a check for this.

> The BERTModel returns output tensors. Giving names to the output tensors / using a dictionary for metadata, etc are pure ONNX abstractions. As an end user, the expectation is that ONNX should produce the same output tensors as PyTorch.

The output hidden_states of [BERTModel](https://huggingface.co/transformers/model_doc/bert.html#bertmodel) is one tensor in PyTorch, but splitted into 12 different tensors when exporting. This is an issue in PyTorch exporter. They will fix it. 

To summarize the issue, 
PyTorch ONNX exporter will fix the duplicated output name issue.
ONNX will add a check that there is no duplicate input and output names
ONNXRuntime will add a check and fail early if model has duplicate input or output names.

I think OnnxRuntime can't add that check to fail early as adding this check could break existing (invalid) models being used via the Python API (which has no issues in case there are dupes). As you said, the onnx checker can be enhanced to add this.

issue.body:
In ```eval``` mode and under ```torch.no_grad()``` context, ```ORTModule``` uses the ```inference_agent``` which uses ```IOBinding``` to execute the graph. ```IOBinding``` only registers a single output for duplicate output names. As a result, when the model has duplicated outputs, the returned values from the ORT backend will only correspond to the ones registered through ```IOBinding```.

An example of duplicate outputs:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/128763932-a90047ff-4ce2-4b1f-95ff-5d6616841388.png)

Example of transformed graph:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/128764004-4d62f957-e647-4cef-8185-0d10d607b97d.png)


These kind of graphs are a result of exporting a ```PyTorch``` model which returns the same value multiple times in its return statement. For example
```py
def forward(self,...):
    out = some_calculation()
    return out, out
```

This pull request addresses this problem by introducing an ```Identity``` op before graph outputs that appear multiple times through a graph transformation.

Replaces https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8605 for context tracking.
